  "bib_entries": {
    "4866413": {
      "title": "Mechanism design for the environment",
      "abstract": "We argue that when externalities such as pollution are nonexcludable, agents must be compelled to participate in a \"mechanism\" to ensure a Pareto-efficient outcome. We survey some of the main findings of the mechanism-design (implementation-theory) literature -- such as the Nash implementation theorem, the Gibbard-Satterthwaite theorem, the Vickrey-Clarke-Groves mechanism, and the Arrow/d'Aspremont-Gerard-Varet mechanism -- and consider their implications for the environment, in particular the reduction of aggregate emissions of pollution. We consider the cases of both complete and incomplete information."
    }
